  "slug": "ackee-and-saltfish",
  "title": "Ackee and saltfish",
  "subtitle": "Jamaica's national dish, a Saturday breakfast",
  "excerpt": "Flaked salt cod folded into soft, buttery ackee with onions, tomato, scotch bonnet, and thyme. The ackee carries the salt from the fish; the scotch bonnet and thyme run through the whole dish. Quick to cook once the cod has soaked. Serves four for breakfast or supper, with hard-dough bread or fried plantain.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Ackee and saltfish became Jamaica's national dish through the convergence of the ackee fruit (brought from West Africa in the 18th century) and preserved salt cod (a colonial trade staple). The combination appears in Jamaican cooking literature from the 19th century onward and is named in the Jamaican Coat of Arms motto.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Ackee and saltfish is Jamaica's national dish: soft, buttery ackee folded into flaked salt cod, with onions, tomato, scotch bonnet, and thyme cooked through it. The ackee carries the salt from the fish; the scotch bonnet and thyme run through the whole pan. Quick to bring together once the cod has soaked. Serves four for breakfast or supper, with hard-dough bread, fried plantain, or boiled green banana.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Two things make or break the dish. The salt cod has to soak long enough to lose most of its salt, and the tinned ackee must be folded in gently at the end so the soft pieces stay whole.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
