      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Soak and prepare the saltfish",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Put the {{salt-cod}} in a large bowl, cover with cold water, and refrigerate. Change the water every 8 to 12 hours for a day or two. The longer the soak, the less salty the finished dish. Taste a small piece before cooking: it should be pleasantly savoury, not aggressively salty. Keep soaking if it is still too salty.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Once soaked, put the fish in a pan of fresh water, bring to a boil, and simmer for 15 minutes. Drain, cool slightly, then flake the flesh away from the skin and bones. Set aside.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cook and combine",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Heat the {{vegetable-oil}} in a wide frying pan over medium-high heat. Add the {{onion}}, {{pepper-red}}, and {{scotch-bonnet}} and cook for 5 minutes until softened.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Add the {{tomato}} and {{thyme}} and cook for 3 more minutes.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Add the flaked saltfish and the {{spring-onion}} and stir to combine. Cook for 2 to 3 minutes.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Drain the {{ackee-tinned}} and fold it through the pan gently. The pieces should warm through but stay whole. Season with {{black-pepper}}; the dish will not need salt. Serve straight away with hard-dough bread, fried plantain, or boiled green banana.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Extend the soak to 48 hours with four water changes. Always taste a piece of the boiled fish before adding it.",
              "cause": "Saltfish not soaked long enough",
              "symptom": "Dish too salty"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add the ackee last and fold it in very gently. It only needs to warm through, a minute or two off the heat is enough.",
              "cause": "Overhandled or overcooked",
              "symptom": "Ackee is mushy"
            },
            {
              "fix": "The tomatoes should release enough liquid. Cook quickly over high heat; this is not a slow-cooked dish.",
              "cause": "Too little oil or too much cooking time",
              "symptom": "Dish too dry"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Ackee and saltfish is the official national dish of Jamaica, and it sits on the breakfast table rather than at dinner, usually on a Saturday or Sunday alongside boiled green bananas, fried plantain, callaloo, and hard-dough bread. The dish brings together ingredients that travelled into Jamaican cooking from different directions: ackee from West Africa, salt cod preserved for the Atlantic trade, scotch bonnet from the wider Caribbean plant heritage.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
